11.	In our text string from September of 2017, Mr. Stio asked what was up with OSY Technologies and I
told him we were getting a quote from it for tokenization for our POS systems. I learned that OSY was using First
Data as its payment processor, and decided to go directly to First Data and OSY for certain merchant services.
That same day I signed the direct contract with First Data and OSY, effective immediately.

From: Jared Isaacman
Sent: Friday, August 23, 2019 11:55:17 AM
To: 'rkerr@firstdata.com'
Subject:

Hi Ryan,

Just wanted to drop you a quick line and check in. I thought our meeting on
Wednesday went well and I think we have a lot of common ground in terms
of what needs to be accomplished through the remainder of the year.
Basically, we see it as the following:

(1) Resolve the open litigation. We are optimistic based on the dialog and
materials exchanged to-date that a settlement is well within reach. I
believe the next step is a response from your side to our settlement
proposal.

(2) Put in place the go-forward referral sales agreement. I know there was a
request for a 30-day extension here, but I don't think that timeline is
necessary or acceptable considering the number of customers caught in
the backlog right now. We have language drafted for an agreement that
includes financial considerations to incentivize FD/Card Connect to send
us volume as well as the usual language around support, ownership of
accounts, etc. in the event the relationship terminates. We can share that at
any time.

(3) Address the OSY/payment facilitator matter. We are open to various
economic structures here, but the bottom line is OSY has been a customer
of Card Connect for years and processes billions. They are a profitable
account for Card Connect (and us a little bit) and they are at risk of leaving.
We need to fix that.

(4) Jointly develop a plan to move forward with respect to at-risk customers
representing over $7B in payment volume. These include: OSY, Shopkeep,
Lavu, MobileBytes, Simpay, POS Nation, etc. I acknowledge that every
situation is a little different, but we ought to jointly call each of these
customers by the end of next week to show a united front and that
FD/Card Connect is committed to getting their problems solved.

(5) Resolve the pricing issue on the SkyTab hardware or remove exclusivity. We
believe the pricing of SkyTab is being unfairly marked up a lot to other
ISOs/competitors... despite the fact that (i) Card Connect imposed
exclusivity of SkyTab for those ISOs and (ii) we developed SkyTab.

(6) Resolve the PAX hardware inventory issue. There must be 5,000+ devices
in that King of Prussia warehouse that we paid for that have never been
deployed.

(7) Agree to terms that protect our customers from solicitation/conversion -
especially by Card Connect direct/Fiserv direct.

(8) Make changes to the referral agreement that reflect the termination
provisions of the operating agreement and improve some other areas
discovered throughout this battle/litigation.

I appreciate the above represents a lot of work. Again, I do think we
have a lot of common ground through which an agreement can be
reached that is mutually beneficial for both parties. I personally, as
well as many others on my team, have dedicated ourselves day and
night to achieve this outcome and look forward to hearing from you to
get it done.

Best,
Jared

   it? That makes no sense.
•  Card Connect has charged whatever they wanted for our software. The pricing was punitive and we haven't made

Jared
